    <item>
      <title>Programs as Flowcharts</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/01-programs-as-flowcharts/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/01-programs-as-flowcharts/index.html</guid>
      <description>We&amp;rsquo;ve created many different computer programs by now, but they have all had one thing in common: they only have a single execution path in the program. This means that, each time we run the program, we&amp;rsquo;ll execute the exact same pieces of code and perform the same operations on each variable. We may have different initial values stored in those variables, but that is really the only difference.
To better visualize this, we can actually think of the execution path of a program just like a flowchart.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Branching Constructs</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/02-branching-constructs/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/02-branching-constructs/index.html</guid>
      <description>Let&amp;rsquo;s take a look at a second flowchart. For this program, we&amp;rsquo;ll have the user input a number. If the number is even, we&amp;rsquo;ll output even, but if it is odd, we&amp;rsquo;ll output odd. Let&amp;rsquo;s look at what this program might look like as a flowchart:
This flowchart uses a diamond-shaped block to indicate a decision we&amp;rsquo;d like our computer program to make. Inside the block, we see the Boolean logic expression x % 2 == 0, which will determine whether x is evenly divisible by $ 2 $.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>If Statements</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/03-if-statements/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/03-if-statements/index.html</guid>
      <description>The first type of conditional construct we&amp;rsquo;ll cover is the if statement. This type of statement allows us to build a block of code which will only be executed if the given Boolean expression evaluates to true.
Here&amp;rsquo;s a simple flowchart that shows an if statement as the conditional construct:
This flowchart represents a program which will ask the user for a number as input, then print that number as output only if the number is greater than $ 0 $.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>If-Else Statements</title>
