    <item>
      <title>Tracing &amp; Testing Branches</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/07-tracing-testing-branches/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/07-tracing-testing-branches/index.html</guid>
      <description>With the introduction of conditional statements, our programs are starting to become more complex. Each time we run the program, it will produce different output based on the input, and some inputs may cause the program to execute different pieces of code entirely. So, we need to develop some more sophisticated testing strategies to help us debug our programs.
Every program should be thoroughly tested. By creating a large number of different test inputs, with each one testing a different part of the program, we can ensure that every line of code is executed at least once when all of our test inputs are used.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Summary</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/08-summary/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc210/04-conditionals/08-summary/index.html</guid>
      <description>In this chapter, we learned all about conditional constructs and how we can use them in our programs. They allow us to build programs that execute different pieces of code depending on inputs provided by the user or the values of variables.
This is one of the first major steps toward building larger and more complex programs. In fact, once we learn how to write programs that can repeat steps, we&amp;rsquo;ll have covered all of the basic building blocks of programming!</description>
